@EndNode


@Node Features "Info about PackX"
* PackX is CLI/Shell utility which allows to pack/unpack or encrypt/decrypt
	files using @{"XPK" Link XPK}.  Never run it from Workbench!

* PackX was written in assembler, that's why it is small and fast.

* PackX can pack files selected by given pattern and scan directories.

* PackX can move or copy packed files to the given directory.

* PackX can be interrupted by Ctrl-C.

* PackX never writes files that are larger when packed.

* PackX can work with the given task priority.

* PackX doesn't change the protection and comment of packing file.  When
	running on V39+, it also saves owner and group ID.

* PackX can add suffix to the packed file and remove suffix from unpacked
	file.  When adding or removing suffix, the source file may (or not)
	be deleted.

* PackX can open progress window on the default or specified public screen.
	Progress window is font-sensitive, but if the screen's font is too
	large, PackX will use topaz/8.  Packing can be aborted by pressing
	@{b}Abort@{ub} gadget or by pressing either @{b}Esc@{ub} or @{b}A@{ub}.
	Note that progress update rate depends of the packer's chunks size,
	so sometimes you will see only 0% and 100%, but the file will be
	packed.

* PackX returns ERROR if some IO error occurs or not enough memory; returns
	INVALID RESIDENT LIBRARY if a library cannot be opened; returns WARN
	if something went wrong with file or xpk returned error, but file
	processing was not stopped (except user break).
@EndNode


@Node Require "Requirements"
PackX needs the following things:

* Kickstart v2.04 (37.175) or newer
* xpkmaster.library v2 or newer  (in LIBS: directory)
* some xpk sublibs  (in LIBS:Compressors directory)

Read @{"XPK" Link XPK} documentation how to install XPK package.
@EndNode


@Node Usage
PackX is CLI/Shell utility.  Never run it from Workbench!

PackX	<file/path> [TO|DEST <path>] [ALL] [LIB|METHOD <lib name>]
	[PWD|PASSWORD <password>] [LOSSY] [SD|STEPDOWN] [NOOW]
	[PRI <priority>] [CS|CHUNKSIZE <size>} [EXT|SUFFIX <suffix>]
	[KEEP] [QUIET] [FORCE] [GUI] [PUBSCR <pubscr>] [DELAY <ticks>]

Template: FILE/M/A,TO=DEST/K,ALL/S,LIB=METHOD/K,PWD=PASSWORD/K,LOSSY/S,
	SD=STEPDOWN/S,NOOW/S,PRI/N,CS=CHUNKSIZE/N,EXT=SUFFIX/N,KEEP/S,
	QUIET/S,FORCE/S,GUI/S,PUBSCR/K,DELAY/N

Where:
FILE - file(s) to pack/unpack/encrypt/decrypt, for example:
	@{b}PackX Buster@{ub}   unpacks file @{i}Buster@{ui}
	@{b}PackX DH1:Docs/#?.txt LIB NUKE@{ub}
		packs all files with @{i}.txt@{ui} suffix in @{i}DH1:Docs@{ui} directory

TO=DEST - a destination path, where to move (or copy if you set KEEP option)
	packed files; if you also set ALL option, all processed files from
	source subdirectiories will be moved/copied, but their directiories
	will not be created

ALL - enable subdirectory scan, for exapmle
	@{b}PackX ALL DH1:Docs ALL LIB NUKE@{ub}
		packs all files and subdirectories in @{i}DH1:Docs@{ui} directory

LIB or METHOD - specifies method to pack file(s) with, for example:
	@{b}PackX DF0:More LIB SHRI.75@{ub}
		packs file @{i}More@{ui} using SHRI method, mode 75

PWD or PASSWORD - specifies password to encrypt/decrypt with, for example:
	@{b}PackX Secret LIB ENCO PWD RosesAreRed@{ub}
		encrypts file @{i}Secret@{ui} using ENCO method
		and password @{i}RosesAreRed@{ui}
	@{b}PackX Secret PWD VioletsAreBlue@{ub}
		deencrypts file @{i}Secret@{ui}
		with password @{i}VioletsAreBlue@{ui}

LOSSY - enables lossy packing (lossy means that file packed with lossy
	packer will not be the same after unpacking as the original.  For
	example JPEG is lossy)

SD or STEPDOWN - enable reducing packing efficiency to save mem if necessary

NOOW - no overwrite; do not delete file that already exists while saving
	output, for example:
	@{b}PackX Demo LIB RLEN NOOW EXT .xpk@{ub}
		packs file @{i}Demo@{ui} and saves it as @{i}Demo.xpk@{ui},
		but if @{i}Demo.xpk@{ui} exists, @{i}Demo@{ui} won't be packed

PRI - set PackX's task priority (-128 to 127), for example:
	@{b}PackX WC.doc PRI 3@{ub}   unpacks file @{i}WC.doc@{ui} with priority 3

CS or CHUNKSIZE - specifies the chunk size; small chunks speeds up packing,
	but reducing pack effeciency.  WARNING:  very small chunk size is
	dangerous and may cause packed files larger that their originals.

EXT or SUFFIX - specifies a suffix to append to the name of the
	packed/encrypted file, and remove from the name of the
	unpacked/decrypted file, for example:
	@{b}PackX S:Start LIB BLZW SUFFIX .xpk@{ub}
		packs file @{i}S:Start@{ui} and saves it as @{i}S:Start.xpk@{ui}
		file @{i}S:Start@{ui} will be removed
	@{b}PackX S:Start.xpk EXT .xpk@{ub}
		unpacks file @{i}S:Start.xpk@{ui} and saves it as @{i}S:Start@{ui}
		file @{i}S:Start.xpk@{ui} will be removed

	NOTE: Extensions are case sensitive.

KEEP - do not delete original file (works with TO=DEST and/or EXT=SUFFIX),
	for example:
	@{b}PackX S:Stop LIB BLZW EXT .xpk KEEP@{ub}
		packs file @{i}S:Stop@{ui} and saves it as @{i}S:Stop.xpk@{ui}
		file @{i}S:Stop@{ui} will not be removed
	@{b}PackX S:Stop.xpk SUFFIX .xpk KEEP@{ub}
		unpacks file @{i}S:Stop.xpk@{ui} and saves it as @{i}S:Stop@{ui}
		file @{i}S:Stop.xpk@{ui} will not be removed

QUIET - enable quiet mode; no progess display, no error messages

FORCE - enable processing files already packed/encrypted with XPK

GUI - open graphical progress window instead of printing progress text in
	the output; all messages are printed in progress window

PUBSCR - specifies the public screen you want the graphical progress window
	be opened; if the given pubscreen doesn't exists, PackX will use the
	default public screen; this option works only in GUI mode; example:
	@{b}PackX Demo.text GUI PUBSCR Workbench@{ub}
		unpacks file @{i}Demo.text@{ui} and displays progress winodw
		on the Workbench screen

DELAY - gives a delay (in ticks; 1/50 sec) between messages displayed on
	progress window; works only in GUI mode; valid values are 0-255
	(from 0 to about 5 seconds)
@EndNode


@Node History
@{b}Version	Date		What was changed@{ub}

 1.0	25-May-95	first release

 1.1	11-Jun-95	removed Enforcer Hit
			new name of temporary file
			added CHUNKSIZE option
			added SD as alias of STEPDOWN
			added SUFFIX option

 1.2	 2-Jul-95	fixed problem with locked files
			added NOOW and KEEP options
			splitted 'file (un)packed' message
			changed version string
			now file attributes are not changed
			fixed error with too long suffix
			few optimizations to reduce the code

 1.3	20-Aug-95	little changes in text formatting
			added GUI and PUBSCR
			now QUIET shuts up PackX for good
			added skipping files if no gain
			skip messages changed to 'Error with'

 1.4	06-Oct-95	added DELAY and DEST
			more legal window calculation
			return WARN in some cases

 1.5	30-Oct-95	fixed suffix problems
			and added "couldn't append suffix" message
			now protection and comment are kept in DEST mode
			now files will be packed if KEEP and Delete
				protection flag not set
@EndNode


@Node Bugs "Bugs Report"
PackX may not work correctly.  If you found any bugs in PackX or in this
guide please contact the author.  The E-Mail address is on the Main page.


@{b}KNOWN PROBELMS:@{ub}
Packing files with pattern in RAM: causes several file scanning.  That's
because PackX uses dos.library's @{b}MatchFirst(), MatchNext(), MatchEnd()@{ub}
functions, which doesn't work correct with files written to RAM: during
scanning.

For example:  @{b}PackX RAM:#? LIB RLEN FORCE@{ub} causes endless packing
(until you break PackX with CTRL-C).


PackX may not work correctly with some file systems (like CrossDOS).

 \\/
+oo+
/||\\
@EndNode


